            <ul>
              <li>Google Sheets wrapper/tool contract</li>
              <li>Gemini TTS wrapper/tool contract</li>
              <li>WhisperX wrapper/tool contract</li>
              <li>scene_bible I/O / locking contract</li>
              <li>OpenRouter dispatch contract for B3</li>
              <li>checkpoint contract</li>
              <li>structured error/escalation contract</li>
            </ul>

            <hr>

            <h3 id="s00-status">Estado geral por componente</h3>

            <h4>Production Manager</h4>
            <p><strong>Verdict:</strong> conceptually solid, operationally incomplete.</p>
            <p>The PM is one of the clearer parts of the architecture, but it still depends critically on <code>read_pub</code> and lacks strong override expiry, data validation and auditability.</p>

            <h4>Video Orchestrator</h4>
            <p><strong>Verdict:</strong> role is right, implementation substrate is not ready.</p>
            <p>VO is currently more specification than executable design. The biggest blocker is the lack of a real protocol for VO ↔ Branch Manager invocation and status handling.</p>

            <h4>B1 — Pre-Production</h4>
            <p><strong>Verdict:</strong> strongest branch in current scope.</p>
            <p>B1 is the best candidate to implement first. The design is disciplined, the agents are mostly well-scoped, and the leverage is high. The big blockers are missing validators and incomplete builder/orchestration docs.</p>

            <h4>B2 — Audio</h4>
            <p><strong>Verdict:</strong> strong architecture, big execution gap.</p>
            <p>B2 looks good in principle, but it is not ready. Too much depends on unimplemented wrappers, unvalidated V3 reuse and weakly specified shared-state handling.</p>

            <h4>B3 — Visual Planning</h4>
            <p><strong>Verdict:</strong> promising but riskier than it looks.</p>
            <p>B3 has a sophisticated structure, but it still needs output validation, deduplication hardening, explicit model choice and tighter grounding to avoid becoming a hallucination engine that pollutes B4.</p>

            <h4>General architecture</h4>
            <p><strong>Verdict:</strong> the conceptual architecture is ahead of the contract architecture.</p>
            <p>This is the central pattern that showed up everywhere.</p>

            <hr>

            <h3 id="s00-top5">Top 5 issues mais importantes</h3>

            <h4>1. Interfaces and contracts are weaker than the component philosophy</h4>
            <p>The architecture explains roles well, but often fails to explain exact payloads, ownership, invocation and failure semantics.</p>

            <h4>2. Video Orchestrator is underspecified where it matters most</h4>
            <p>Its role is clear, but its actual operational protocol is not. That makes it dangerous to implement too early.</p>

            <h4>3. scene_bible is central but still not protected enough</h4>
            <p>Multiple branches depend on reading/writing it, but locking, merging, atomic writes and ownership are not hardened.</p>

            <h4>4. The deterministic skill layer is missing</h4>
            <p>A lot of the system still assumes critical skills already exist. They do not.</p>

            <h4>5. B2 and B3 look more production-ready than they actually are</h4>
            <p>Both are good specs, but operationally they still hide substantial unresolved complexity.</p>

            <hr>

            <h3 id="s00-suggestions">Top 5 sugestões de melhoria</h3>

            <h4>1. Harden schemas and invocation protocols before building more orchestration</h4>
            <p>Write the contracts first. Especially: PM job artifact, scene_bible, B3 compiled_entities, checkpoints, VO ↔ BM invocation.</p>

            <h4>2. Build the deterministic substrate before the orchestrator layer</h4>
            <p>Prioritize: <code>read_pub</code>, B1 validators, B2 wrappers, <code>bible_updater</code>, schema validation.</p>

            <h4>3. Implement B1 first as the first truly real branch</h4>
            <p>It is the strongest mix of leverage, clarity, and low cost.</p>

            <h4>4. Treat scene_bible I/O as shared infrastructure, not a helper</h4>
            <p>It needs explicit lock/merge/versioning semantics.</p>

            <h4>5. Stop deferring key model/tool decisions</h4>
            <p>Especially in B3. Pick defaults now, benchmark later. Deferred decisions are implementation debt.</p>

            <hr>

            <h3 id="s00-docquality">Overall note on documentation quality</h3>
            <p><strong>Score: 7.8 / 10</strong></p>

            <h4>Why this is a strong score</h4>
            <p>Because the docs are: serious, intentional, system-aware, much better than average agent-architecture documentation, clearly shaped by real production pain from V3.</p>

            <h4>Why it is not higher</h4>
            <p>Because there is still too much gap between: <strong>role clarity</strong> and <strong>runtime contract clarity</strong>, <strong>high-level architecture</strong> and <strong>implementation substrate</strong>, <strong>beautiful branch decomposition</strong> and <strong>real deterministic tooling</strong>.</p>
            <p>In other words: <strong>the docs are good enough to guide a system, but not yet good enough to guarantee a low-friction implementation.</strong></p>

            <hr>

            <h3 id="s00-final">Final conclusion</h3>
            <p>The project is in a good place strategically. The architecture is not fake. The thought is real. The separation of responsibilities is good. The hierarchy makes sense. The branch design is mostly intelligent.</p>
            <p>But the next step is no longer more ideation. The next step is to:</p>
            <ol>
              <li>harden contracts</li>
              <li>build the deterministic skills</li>
              <li>implement B1 first</li>
              <li>bring B2 and B3 into reality carefully</li>
              <li>only then let VO become the real orchestrator</li>
            </ol>
            <p>If you do that in the right order, this can become a real operating system for the department.</p>
            <p>If you skip that order and jump too early into orchestration polish, you'll create a lot of elegant-looking integration debt.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

