          <li>OpenRouter dispatch contract for B3</li>
          <li>checkpoint contract</li>
          <li>structured error/escalation contract</li>
        </ul>

        <hr>

        <h2 id="s00-estado">Estado Geral por Componente</h2>
        <h3>Production Manager</h3>
        <p><strong>Verdict:</strong> conceptually solid, operationally incomplete. The PM is one of the clearer parts of the architecture, but it still depends critically on <code>read_pub</code> and lacks strong override expiry, data validation and auditability.</p>
        <h3>Video Orchestrator</h3>
        <p><strong>Verdict:</strong> role is right, implementation substrate is not ready. VO is currently more specification than executable design. The biggest blocker is the lack of a real protocol for VO ↔ Branch Manager invocation and status handling.</p>
        <h3>B1 — Pre-Production</h3>
        <p><strong>Verdict:</strong> strongest branch in current scope. B1 is the best candidate to implement first. The design is disciplined, the agents are mostly well-scoped, and the leverage is high. The big blockers are missing validators and incomplete builder/orchestration docs.</p>
        <h3>B2 — Audio</h3>
        <p><strong>Verdict:</strong> strong architecture, big execution gap. B2 looks good in principle, but it is not ready. Too much depends on unimplemented wrappers, unvalidated V3 reuse and weakly specified shared-state handling.</p>
        <h3>B3 — Visual Planning</h3>
        <p><strong>Verdict:</strong> promising but riskier than it looks. B3 has a sophisticated structure, but it still needs output validation, deduplication hardening, explicit model choice and tighter grounding to avoid becoming a hallucination engine that pollutes B4.</p>
        <h3>General Architecture</h3>
        <p><strong>Verdict:</strong> the conceptual architecture is ahead of the contract architecture. This is the central pattern that showed up everywhere.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2 id="s00-top5">Top 5 Issues Mais Importantes</h2>
        <h3>1. Interfaces and contracts are weaker than the component philosophy</h3>
        <p>The architecture explains roles well, but often fails to explain exact payloads, ownership, invocation and failure semantics.</p>
        <h3>2. Video Orchestrator is underspecified where it matters most</h3>
        <p>Its role is clear, but its actual operational protocol is not. That makes it dangerous to implement too early.</p>
        <h3>3. scene_bible is central but still not protected enough</h3>
        <p>Multiple branches depend on reading/writing it, but locking, merging, atomic writes and ownership are not hardened.</p>
        <h3>4. The deterministic skill layer is missing</h3>
        <p>A lot of the system still assumes critical skills already exist. They do not.</p>
        <h3>5. B2 and B3 look more production-ready than they actually are</h3>
        <p>Both are good specs, but operationally they still hide substantial unresolved complexity.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2 id="s00-top5s">Top 5 Sugestões de Melhoria</h2>
        <h3>1. Harden schemas and invocation protocols before building more orchestration</h3>
        <p>Write the contracts first. Especially: PM job artifact, scene_bible, B3 compiled_entities, checkpoints, VO ↔ BM invocation.</p>
        <h3>2. Build the deterministic substrate before the orchestrator layer</h3>
        <p>Prioritize: <code>read_pub</code>, B1 validators, B2 wrappers, <code>bible_updater</code>, schema validation.</p>
        <h3>3. Implement B1 first as the first truly real branch</h3>
        <p>It is the strongest mix of leverage, clarity, and low cost.</p>
        <h3>4. Treat scene_bible I/O as shared infrastructure, not a helper</h3>
        <p>It needs explicit lock/merge/versioning semantics.</p>
        <h3>5. Stop deferring key model/tool decisions</h3>
        <p>Especially in B3. Pick defaults now, benchmark later. Deferred decisions are implementation debt.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2 id="s00-docs">Overall Note on Documentation Quality</h2>
        <h3>Score: 7.8 / 10</h3>
        <p>The docs are serious, intentional, system-aware, much better than average agent-architecture documentation, and clearly shaped by real production pain from V3.</p>
        <p>Why it is not higher: there is still too much gap between <strong>role clarity</strong> and <strong>runtime contract clarity</strong>, between <strong>high-level architecture</strong> and <strong>implementation substrate</strong>, and between <strong>beautiful branch decomposition</strong> and <strong>real deterministic tooling</strong>.</p>
        <p>In other words: <strong>the docs are good enough to guide a system, but not yet good enough to guarantee a low-friction implementation.</strong></p>

        <hr>

        <h2 id="s00-conclusion">Final Conclusion</h2>
        <p>The project is in a good place strategically. The architecture is not fake. The thought is real. The separation of responsibilities is good. The hierarchy makes sense. The branch design is mostly intelligent.</p>
        <p>But the next step is no longer more ideation. The next step is to:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>harden contracts</li>
          <li>build the deterministic skills</li>
          <li>implement B1 first</li>
          <li>bring B2 and B3 into reality carefully</li>
          <li>only then let VO become the real orchestrator</li>
        </ol>
        <p>If you do that in the right order, this can become a real operating system for the department. If you skip that order and jump too early into orchestration polish, you'll create a lot of elegant-looking integration debt.</p>
      </div>
